(44, 7, 37, 41, 9, 7, 7, 'him shall ye hear', 'Prophetic Voice Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of prophetic authority. In Acts, Moses speaks of a prophet to be heard, while in Mark, God commands to ''hear him,'' referring to Jesus, thus linking their roles as prophets.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 37, 42, 9, 30, 31, 'A prophet shall the Lord your God raise up', 'Moses and Prophetic Fulfillment', 'This connection highlights the role of Moses as a prophet, as indicated in Acts 7:37, and the appearance of Moses in Luke 9:30-31, where he speaks of Jesus'' impending death. Both passages emphasize the prophetic significance of Moses in relation to Jesus.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 38, 45, 3, 2, 2, 'lively oracles to give unto us', 'Connection of Oracles in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the significance of the ''oracles'' given to the Israelites. Both passages emphasize the role of these divine communications in their respective contexts.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 38, 58, 5, 12, 12, 'oracles to give unto us', 'Connection of Oracles of God', 'This connection highlights the concept of ''oracles'' in both passages. Acts 7:38 refers to the ''lively oracles'' received in the wilderness, while Hebrews 5:12 discusses the ''oracles of God'' as foundational teachings.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 38, 5, 33, 4, 4, 'received the lively oracles to give unto us', 'Moses and the Law Connection', 'This connection highlights Moses'' role in delivering the law to the Israelites. Both passages emphasize the importance of the law received by Moses for the congregation of Jacob.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 38, 43, 1, 17, 17, 'lively oracles to give unto us', 'Law and Grace Connection', 'This connection highlights the transition from the law given by Moses to the grace and truth brought by Jesus Christ. Acts 7:38 refers to the ''lively oracles'' received, which can be seen as the law, while John 1:17 contrasts this with the grace and truth that Jesus embodies.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 38, 44, 7, 53, 53, 'received the lively oracles', 'Connection of Law and Angels', 'Both passages emphasize the role of angels in delivering the law. The first mentions ''the lively oracles'' received, while the second states the law was received ''by the disposition of angels.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 38, 60, 4, 11, 11, 'lively oracles to give unto us', 'Connection of Oracles in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the concept of ''oracles'' as divine communication. Both passages emphasize the importance of speaking and ministering as representatives of God''s words.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 38, 5, 5, 27, 31, 'received the lively oracles', 'Connection of Divine Communication', 'Both passages emphasize the role of Moses as a mediator between God and the people, highlighting the importance of receiving divine commandments. Acts 7:38 refers to Moses receiving ''lively oracles,'' while Deuteronomy 5:27-31 discusses the people''s desire to hear God''s words through Moses.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 39, 4, 14, 3, 4, 'turned back again into Egypt', 'Rejection of God''s Guidance', 'Both passages emphasize a desire to return to Egypt, reflecting disobedience and lack of faith in God''s plan. The Israelites in Acts 7:39 are described as turning back to Egypt in their hearts, paralleling the lament in Numbers 14:3-4 about returning to Egypt due to fear and doubt.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 39, 4, 11, 5, 5, 'turned back again into Egypt', 'Rejection of Egypt''s Influence', 'This connection highlights the Israelites'' longing for Egypt after rejecting Moses. Both passages emphasize a desire to return to the comforts of Egypt, illustrating their disobedience and nostalgia for former provisions.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 39, 16, 9, 16, 17, 'turned back again into Egypt', 'Rebellion and Return to Bondage', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of rebellion against God and a desire to return to Egypt or bondage. They highlight the refusal to obey God''s commandments and the hardening of hearts, illustrating a pattern of disobedience among the people.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 39, 2, 16, 3, 3, 'turned back again into Egypt', 'Israel''s Rebellion and Longing for Egypt', 'This connection highlights the Israelites'' disobedience and desire to return to Egypt. Both passages emphasize a longing for the comforts of Egypt despite the hardships faced in the wilderness.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 39, 26, 20, 6, 14, 'would not obey', 'Rebellion Against God', 'Both passages emphasize the rebellion of the Israelites against God after being delivered from Egypt. Acts 7:39 highlights their refusal to obey, while Ezekiel 20:6-14 details their continued idolatry and disobedience. This connection highlights a recurring theme of rejection of divine guidance.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 39, 44, 7, 51, 52, 'would not obey', 'Resistance to God''s Message', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of resistance to God''s chosen leaders. In Acts 7:39, the fathers rejected Moses, paralleling the accusation in Acts 7:51-52 that the current generation resists the Holy Ghost like their ancestors did.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 39, 2, 14, 11, 12, 'turned back again into Egypt', 'Rejection of Leadership and Egypt', 'Both passages emphasize a desire to return to Egypt, highlighting the Israelites'' rejection of Moses'' leadership. In Acts, the phrase ''turned back again into Egypt'' reflects their longing for the past, similar to the complaints in Exodus about preferring servitude in Egypt over facing hardship in the wilderness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 40, 2, 32, 1, 1, 'for as for this Moses, which brought us out of the land of Egypt, we wot not what is become of him.', 'Connection of Idolatry and Leadership', 'Both passages emphasize the people''s demand for gods in the absence of Moses. This connection highlights their impatience and desire for visible leadership when Moses is delayed.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 40, 2, 32, 23, 23, 'as for this Moses, which brought us out of the land of Egypt', 'Connection of Idolatry and Leadership', 'Both passages emphasize the people''s demand for gods in the absence of Moses, highlighting their impatience and desire for leadership. The repetition of the phrase ''as for this Moses'' underscores their confusion regarding his fate.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 41, 19, 106, 19, 21, 'made a calf in those days', 'Idolatry and Forgetting God', 'Both passages emphasize the act of making a calf and worshipping it, highlighting the theme of idolatry. They also reflect on the people''s forgetfulness of God, who had performed great deeds for them.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 41, 16, 9, 18, 18, 'made a calf', 'Idolatry and the Golden Calf', 'Both passages emphasize the creation of a calf and the worship associated with it. They highlight the Israelites'' rejection of God through idolatry, showcasing their disobedience and provocations.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 41, 28, 9, 1, 1, 'rejoiced in the works of their own hands', 'Idolatry and False Joy', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of idolatry leading to false joy. Acts 7:41 describes the Israelites rejoicing in their idol, while Hosea 9:1 warns Israel against rejoicing due to their unfaithfulness to God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 41, 28, 9, 10, 10, 'rejoiced in the works of their own hands', 'Idolatry and Abomination Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of idolatry, with Acts mentioning the ''calf'' and Hosea referencing ''Baalâ€“peor'' as examples of Israel''s turning away from God. This connection highlights the consequences of their actions, described as ''abominations'' in Hosea.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 41, 35, 2, 18, 20, 'the works of their own hands', 'Idolatry and Its Consequences', 'Both passages emphasize the futility of idol worship, highlighting the contrast between man-made idols and the living God. Acts 7:41 describes the creation of an idol, while Habakkuk 2:18-20 questions the value of such graven images.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 41, 66, 9, 20, 20, 'works of their own hands', 'Idolatry and Works of Hands', 'Both passages emphasize the act of worshiping idols made by human hands. Acts 7:41 describes the Israelites rejoicing in the works of their own hands, while Revelation 9:20 warns against the works of their hands leading to idol worship.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 41, 2, 32, 2, 8, 'rejoiced in the works of their own hands', 'Idolatry and Sacrifice Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of making a calf and offering sacrifices to it. Acts 7:41 references the people''s rejoicing in their own works, paralleling Exodus 32:2-8 where they proclaim the calf as their god and celebrate with offerings.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 42, 30, 5, 25, 26, 'forty years in the wilderness', 'Wilderness Sacrifices and Idolatry', 'Both passages emphasize the Israelites'' sacrifices in the wilderness and their idolatry. Acts 7:42 references the forty years of offerings, paralleling Amos 5:25-26''s mention of sacrifices while also condemning the worship of Moloch and Chiun.', 'theme', 0.489, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 42, 26, 20, 39, 39, 'O ye house of Israel', 'Idolatry and Divine Rejection', 'This connection highlights the theme of Israel''s idolatry and God''s response. Both passages emphasize God''s rejection of Israel''s worship due to their devotion to idols.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 42, 24, 19, 13, 13, 'worship the host of heaven', 'Worship of the Host of Heaven', 'This connection highlights the theme of idolatry and the worship of celestial beings. Both passages address the act of offering sacrifices and incense to the host of heaven, indicating a rejection of true worship.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 7, 42, 19, 81, 11, 12, 'gave them up', 'Divine Abandonment Theme', 'Both passages emphasize God''s response to Israel''s disobedience. Acts 7:42 mentions God giving them up, paralleling Psalms 81:11-12, where God gives them up to their own desires.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
